<subSubSection id="9448CC006D4C98A6B7C75969657CD73C" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="5C50CC3A1F2F0E00F939264DA4AC590D" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
Genus 
<taxonomicName id="72B073ACF1A26D489B8C43743B88C597" LSID="9E249B1E-F540-5203-B000-DD87278999DA" authority="Chemnitz, 1786" authorityName="Chemnitz" authorityYear="1786" class="Gastropoda" family="Hygromiidae" genus="Trochulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trochulus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Trochulus Chemnitz, 1786</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FC2F498A2CCE3E18A0AE8BDAE83488AC" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="FF2631A3AD7C1992CB13697267146D0F" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
<taxonomicName id="978DBCA77C46D3B810029D5E0A4EFF7A" baseAuthorityName="Eder" baseAuthorityYear="1917" class="Gastropoda" family="Hygromiidae" genus="Trochulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trochulus biconicus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="biconicus">Trochulus biconicus</taxonomicName>
(Eder, 1917)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6C350487AE663BC3A689AE0D3B9D59D4" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A3F356EA6E0B80CF3695A52437E0EA08" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="75442426D086FC83120EF193EFC8B3C7" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Shell flattened and thin-walled, translucent, compressed in the direction of the axis; no trichome formation; whorls 5.5-6, gradually increasing so that the body whorl is only about twice as wide as the first whorl; the aperture is oblique, narrow, crescent-shaped; lip sharp, whitish and slightly reflexed; the four mucous glands are long, thick and pointed; penis and epiphallus are about the same length; the flagellum is barely separated from the epiphallus.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6F7D8A80ECB3D226F5610CAA5BDEE615" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="0DEA5B4820F82BCF78AE160100E71AE1" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F795DECD72CE20648B633947C2B2ED13" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
<taxonomicName id="35F9DE2D215FB578181A247EBD4DEC77" authorityName="Kneubühler &amp; Baggenstos &amp; Neubert" authorityYear="2022" family="Hygromiidae" genus="Raeticella" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Raeticella" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9F6C4F890F4788195796161278ED56E0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Raeticella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. nov. differs from 
<taxonomicName id="447AAB2348530A0203980B6F1D021882" authorityName="Chemnitz" authorityYear="1786" class="Gastropoda" family="Hygromiidae" genus="Trochulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trochulus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="13EC79247D9ECD426620DFA048F1B1BB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Trochulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a flat, biconical shell, devoid of any periostracal hairs, even in juveniles, and in having only four instead of occasionally six or eight (see 
<bibRefCitation id="59134E746D580EBF3CE64702E0E7FD35" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/mollus/eyu023" author="Duda, M" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Molluscan Studies" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="371 - 387" refId="B13" refString="Duda, M, Kruckenhauser, L, Sattmann, H, Harl, J, Jaksch, K, Haring, E, 2014. Differentiation in the Trochulus hispidus complex and related taxa (Pulmonata: Hygromiidae): morphology, ecology and their relation to phylogeography. Journal of Molluscan Studies 80 (4): 371 - 387, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/mollus/eyu023" title="Differentiation in the Trochulus hispidus complex and related taxa (Pulmonata: Hygromiidae): morphology, ecology and their relation to phylogeography." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/mollus/eyu023" volume="80" year="2014">Duda et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
) mucous glands. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="B51815CDC476D2F442ED7A51A538D90D" authorityName="Neiber, Razkin &amp; Hausdorf" authorityYear="2017" class="Gastropoda" family="Hygromiidae" genus="Noricella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Noricella" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B35BF13D8625F28C7AC500FB697B0490" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Noricella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by lacking a basal tooth, being devoid of any periostracal hairs, the absence of coarse ripples and the absence of an additional fold and bulge in the penial papilla, which occurs in 
<taxonomicName id="DB28FC46AC306981D129B1AC560ECD7B" genus="N." lsidName="N. oreinos" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="oreinos">
<emphasis id="AFAB367CC16F160FF2DD91913F5BB1C4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">N. oreinos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="63A558FCB155DC16E906342490DB256F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/mollus/eyu023" author="Duda, M" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Molluscan Studies" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="371 - 387" refId="B13" refString="Duda, M, Kruckenhauser, L, Sattmann, H, Harl, J, Jaksch, K, Haring, E, 2014. Differentiation in the Trochulus hispidus complex and related taxa (Pulmonata: Hygromiidae): morphology, ecology and their relation to phylogeography. Journal of Molluscan Studies 80 (4): 371 - 387, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/mollus/eyu023" title="Differentiation in the Trochulus hispidus complex and related taxa (Pulmonata: Hygromiidae): morphology, ecology and their relation to phylogeography." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/mollus/eyu023" volume="80" year="2014">Duda et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="727C1DCCE838A039919B2B21C270A096" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0FC1CEF4DF3A1B8A5F086EB7B9E9D085" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C5B0FEDDF8B1F97C1249C6A4BE30DE11" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
The name is derived from the Roman province of Raetia, which comprised within its larger expansion, the area of what is now known as eastern and central Switzerland. It also refers to the generic name, 
<taxonomicName id="DE56AD20C8EE496B267C766FB0976816" authorityName="Neiber, Razkin &amp; Hausdorf" authorityYear="2017" class="Gastropoda" family="Hygromiidae" genus="Noricella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Noricella" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A514B2B502A0CC9C37DE62EC988990C9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Noricella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is another recently detected spin-off from 
<taxonomicName id="A329C2F0B8D0AAC0DBF40ED8AAE0974E" authorityName="Chemnitz" authorityYear="1786" class="Gastropoda" family="Hygromiidae" genus="Trochulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trochulus" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83412E84129837081D6681C03EFE2DFA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Trochulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and whose name derives in part from the eastern border province of Raetia (Noricum - now Austria and Slovenia).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
